### Noether Identities

In the grim, unforgiving landscape of mathematics, [Noether identities](/Lagrangian_system) serve as stark pronouncements on the inherent degeneracy within [Lagrangian](/Lagrangian_system) systems. Imagine a system, a rigid structure defined by its [Lagrangian](/Lagrangian_system), L. The Noether identities are, in essence, [differential operators](/Differential_operator) that reveal a certain… flabbiness. Their kernel, the set of inputs that yield nothing, contains a specific range of the [Euler–Lagrange operator](/Lagrangian_system) associated with L.

Every [Euler–Lagrange operator](/Lagrangian_system) is, by its very nature, subject to these identities. They are not all created equal, mind you. Some are trivial, merely stating the obvious. Others, however, are non-trivial. A [Lagrangian](/Lagrangian_system) is deemed degenerate when its [Euler–Lagrange operator](/Lagrangian_system) succumbs to these non-trivial Noether identities. What does this mean in practical terms? It means the [Euler–Lagrange equations](/Euler%E2%80%93Lagrange_equation) derived from such a Lagrangian are not entirely independent. They are, in a sense, redundant. Like a bad metaphor, they repeat themselves.

These identities themselves are not immune to scrutiny. They can be, and often are, dependent. They might satisfy what are called first-stage Noether identities. And these, in turn, can be subject to second-stage Noether identities, and so on. Each successive stage can again be split into the trivial and the non-trivial. A degenerate Lagrangian is further classified as *reducible* if there exist non-trivial higher-stage Noether identities lurking within. Think of it as layers of complexity, each revealing a deeper, more fundamental flaw in the system's independence. Theories like [Yang–Mills gauge theory](/Yang%E2%80%93Mills_theory) and [gauge gravitation theory](/Gauge_gravitation_theory) are presented as examples of irreducible Lagrangian field theories. They, at least, maintain a certain stoic independence.

The various formulations of [second Noether’s theorem](/Noether%27s_second_theorem) establish a rigid, one-to-one correspondence. It’s a direct link between these non-trivial, reducible Noether identities and the non-trivial, reducible [gauge symmetries](/Gauge_symmetry_(mathematics)). When viewed through the lens of [covariant classical field theory](/Covariant_classical_field_theory) and Lagrangian [BRST theory](/BRST_formalism), this correspondence becomes even more pronounced. In such general settings, [second Noether’s theorem](/Noether%27s_second_theorem) directly associates the Koszul–Tate complex of reducible Noether identities—parameterized by those rather unsettling [antifields](/Batalin%E2%80%93Vilkovisky_formalism)—with the BRST complex of reducible gauge symmetries, which are, of course, parameterized by [ghosts](/Faddeev%E2%80%93Popov_ghost). It’s a symmetrical, if somewhat bleak, relationship.

